-- Natural Induction (and Strong Induction)
--
-- STATUS: CONCEPTUAL (Issue #117)
-- This file EXPLAINS how induction works in CredTT but does not demonstrate
-- actual recursive proofs, which require a Nat data type with induction principle.
-- The key insight: credence can degrade through induction steps.
--
-- Classical: P(0) and (forall n. P(n) -> P(n+1)) implies forall n. P(n)
-- CredTT: Result may DEGRADE unless step is contractive
--         base @ c_b, step @ c_s -> result depends on contractivity
--
-- Example: Prove sum(1..n) = n(n+1)/2
-- Base: sum(1..0) = 0 = 0*1/2 = 0
-- Step: If sum(1..n) = n(n+1)/2, then sum(1..n+1) = (n+1)(n+2)/2

-- Classical induction: definite result
-- CredTT induction: MIGHT degrade over steps

-- Base case at credence c_b
postulate base : sum_0_eq_0 @ c_b

-- Inductive step at credence c_s
postulate step : step_preserves @ c_s

-- In classical logic: P(0) and (P(n)->P(n+1)) gives forall n. P(n)
-- In CredTT: what is the credence of P(n) for large n?

-- If step has credence < 1, each application DEGRADES:
-- P(0) @ c_b
-- P(1) @ c_b * c_s
-- P(2) @ c_b * c_s^2
-- ...
-- P(n) @ c_b * c_s^n

-- If c_s < 1, this goes to ZERO as n -> infinity!
-- The "infinite" case of induction has credence 0

-- This is WHY CredTT is more honest than classical logic:
-- Induction over infinite sets is NOT automatic
-- Each step accumulates uncertainty

-- CONTRACTIVE INDUCTION:
-- If the step is CONTRACTIVE (non-degrading), credence preserved

-- Step at credence 1 (contractive)
postulate contractive_step : step_at_one @ 1

-- Now: P(n) @ c_b * 1^n = c_b
-- Credence is preserved! Induction is safe.

-- The lesson: induction is only as good as its step
-- Classical logic hides this; CredTT exposes it

-- STRONG INDUCTION:
-- Assume P(0), P(1), ..., P(n-1) to prove P(n)
-- Same issue: credence can degrade

-- With contractive step (credence 1), the step is stable
stable contractive_step

-- Note: base and step with variable credences c_b and c_s have Unknown stability
-- To demonstrate stable induction, use concrete credence 1. See issue #182.

-- The KEY insight:
-- Classical induction assumes infinite steps at no cost
-- CredTT induction tracks the cost of each step
